WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.180
So yeah, I'll focus on epigenetic modification in T cell lymphomas and some of the older

00:00:06.180 --> 00:00:08.500
strategies and some of the newer strategies with that.

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:10.780
These are my disclosures.

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:16.300
And then objective, because we're talking about epigenetic dysregulation, I think TFH

00:00:16.300 --> 00:00:17.740
lymphomas will be the focus.

00:00:18.160 --> 00:00:22.620
And we'll be talking about the two main trials, the ROCHOP trial and the ORACLE trial.

00:00:23.300 --> 00:00:30.400
And then also end with emergence of the EZH1-2 inhibitors so far that we know of.

00:00:31.180 --> 00:00:41.160
Okay, so there was a major update in the classification of PTCL subtypes, especially in the 2022 WHO

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:41.660
edition.

00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:49.520
All the basically angiomelblastic T cell lymphoma, follicular T cell, and PTCL with TFH phenotype

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:52.560
were all just categorized as nodal TFH lymphomas.

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:57.340
Either angiomelblastic, follicular type, or NOS.

00:00:58.060 --> 00:00:59.360
So that was a major change.

00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:09.020
As we know, these nodal TFH lymphomas are characterized by epigenetic mutations, especially

00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:12.620
TET2, DNMT3A, IDH2, and ROA.

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:18.160
And obviously those are common and may predict responses to epigenetic therapies.

00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:21.980
They also, there was a change in terms of

00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:29.920
having a category called primary nodal EBV, EBV positive lymphomas also with this edition.

00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:32.320
So focusing more on the AITL.

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:37.460
So AITL is a very complex, it's, it's, the pathogenesis is complex because there's a

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:42.560
lot of interplay between the follicular helper T cells and the germinal center B cells,

00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:44.560
the T cells, eosinophils.

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:52.940
CXCL, CXCL13 is released by, by the TFH cell, which helps actually,

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:56.180
in recruitment of the germinal center B cells.

00:01:56.520 --> 00:01:58.180
So there's, there's a lot of interplay.

00:01:59.100 --> 00:02:04.400
There's increased production of VEGF, which leads to angiogenesis and overall leads to

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:07.160
development of this, this lymphoma.

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:14.860
If we look at mutational hierarchy, the, the mutations such as TET2 and DNMT3A are

00:02:14.860 --> 00:02:22.820
common at the progenitor level and later cells can derive other mutations.

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:26.120
That can lead to either myeloid malignancies or lymphomas.

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:33.620
So if you have TET2 or DNMT3A mutation, that's passed on to the, the lymphoma progenitor cells,

00:02:33.620 --> 00:02:44.680
you do require the second hit with either ROA, IDH2, CD28, or PLC-gamma mutations to develop AITL.

00:02:45.620 --> 00:02:52.700
If you develop, sorry, not one mutation, then it will lead to development of truly a

00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:56.720
B-cell lymphoma, which we see sometimes with AITL.

00:02:58.460 --> 00:03:03.400
So looking at the treatment pathways, there's many, many treatment pathways that are

00:03:03.400 --> 00:03:06.120
obviously being targeted for PTCL.

00:03:06.980 --> 00:03:12.180
And I'm not going to go over all of them, but obviously PI3 kinase pathway is important.

00:03:12.820 --> 00:03:14.660
JAK2 inhibition is important.

00:03:14.860 --> 00:03:22.580
We talked about the CD30 targeting, but if you go inside the nucleus, what I want to focus on is

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:24.500
three main pathways.

00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:29.820
One is demethylation with the DNMT3A inhibitors.

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:35.040
We got HDAC inhibitors and then EZH1 slash 2 inhibitors.

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:45.160
So HDAC inhibitors, which increase the acetylation and result in gene activation,

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:48.400
have been very effective in PTCL.

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:52.520
I guess I wouldn't, I shouldn't say very effective, but they're more,

00:03:52.540 --> 00:03:56.060
more effective in AITL subtype than other T-cell lymphomas.

00:03:56.840 --> 00:04:00.760
And, you know, obviously this is the mechanism of how they work.

00:04:00.920 --> 00:04:07.700
If you inhibit the HDAC, which will result in hyperacetylation of the DNA,

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:16.540
which will open up the DNA for reading and will activate tumor suppressor genes.

00:04:19.400 --> 00:04:21.540
Multiple retrospective studies have shown,

00:04:22.500 --> 00:04:29.380
that these HDAC inhibitors are very effective in TFH type of lymphomas.

00:04:30.280 --> 00:04:36.460
Now, this is something that we found out recently, probably in 2018, 2019, 2020.

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:42.780
But before that was known, a clinical trial was designed called the RhoCHOP versus

00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:46.720
CHOP trial, RhoCHOP trial, where romodepsin was added to CHOP.

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:52.420
Now, because we didn't know about the activity,

00:04:52.420 --> 00:04:52.480
we didn't know about the activity, we didn't know about the activity,

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:55.480
of the HDAC inhibitors in TFH lymphomas,

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:02.520
this trial was not stratified based on the TFH versus non-TFH.

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:07.680
So although there were about 50% of the patients who had AITL in both arms,

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:15.480
it did include other 50% of patients who had PTCL-NOS or anaplastic large cell lymphoma.

00:05:17.020 --> 00:05:20.040
With that, the results were,

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:27.040
they showed that the median progression of resurvival was slightly improved with the RhoCHOP,

00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:32.800
but it was not clinically or statistically significant, 12 versus 10 months.

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:35.340
And then the overall survival was the same also.

00:05:36.920 --> 00:05:42.540
The investigators went back and looked at just the TFH phenotype of lymphomas recently.

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:49.460
And at that point, they did find that if you add romodepsin to CHOP for specifically the TFH

00:05:49.460 --> 00:05:51.360
lymphomas, then the PFS is improved.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:54.640
So the results were 19.5 versus 10.6.

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:57.260
But obviously, this is a post-hoc analysis.

00:05:57.260 --> 00:06:01.880
And because of that, it hasn't really made any guidelines.

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:13.120
Similarly, if you look at azacitidine, which is obviously inhibitor of DNMT,

00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:19.720
that has been compared to standard of care, specifically in the TFH phenotype lymphomas with this trial.

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:21.860
So this trial only included patients who had TFH phenotype lymphomas.

00:06:21.860 --> 00:06:22.120
So this trial only included patients who had TFH phenotype lymphomas with this trial.

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:24.920
So this trial only included patients who had TFH phenotype lymphomas, which predict for hopefully

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:27.720
better responses with hypomethylating agents.

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:31.960
And the standard of care was either benamastine, romodepsin, or gemcitabine with this.

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:41.000
And with this study, there was improvement in PFS of 5.6 versus 2.8 months.

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:47.640
But the way that the trial was designed, the p-value needed to be less than 0.025

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:51.840
to meet statistical significance, which it did not.

00:06:51.840 --> 00:07:04.680
But to me, I think this shows that this treatment is actually effective in a lymphoma that really doesn't have many options.

00:07:04.680 --> 00:07:11.840
There was also improvement in overall survival, obviously too early to tell, but there was improvement of about eight months.

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:19.640
One of the other things that we learned from this trial is that it proved the mutations that we already knew about with TFH lymphomas,

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:26.560
most common ones were TET2, almost about 80%, followed by the ROA, IDH2, and the DNM2/3A mutations.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:32.160
And lastly, I want to focus on the EZH1/EZH2 inhibitors.

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:41.760
So PRC2 complex is important for trimethylation of the histone H3, which shuts down transcription

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:45.040
and decreases the tumor suppressor effects.

00:07:46.400 --> 00:07:49.360
And EZH1 and EZH2 are super important.

00:07:49.360 --> 00:08:00.520
So if you have a drug that can inhibit this PRC2 complex, which would hopefully result in less trimethylation

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:05.320
and activation of the transcription, that would result in more tumor suppressive effects.

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:14.120
So with that, while metastat was investigated in a large phase two study, where overall responses

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:19.080
were quite good for PTCL/TFH phenotype or AIT.

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:21.440
And we were able to find out that the PTCL/TFH very good for PTCL/TPH phenotype and AITL almost 50% to 60%.

00:08:22.240 --> 00:08:24.400
Including some CR rates.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:30.720
Although this has been published, it has not made the NCCN guidelines,

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:33.680
nor is it FDA approved.

00:08:33.680 --> 00:08:38.480
And currently, I'm not aware of where this drug is going in terms of further development

00:08:39.120 --> 00:08:40.320
for T cell lymphomas.

00:08:41.920 --> 00:08:48.480
A case scenario that I just wanted to briefly go over was, we had a patient who had multiple myeloma and they had, you know, we had a patient who had multiple myeloma and they had, you know, multiple myeloma and they had, you know, multiple myeloma and they had, you know, multiple myeloma and they had, you know, multiple myeloma and they had, you know, multiple myeloma and they had, you know, multiple myeloma and they had, you know, multiple myeloma.

00:08:48.480 --> 00:08:51.840
And they had CAR-T for that, cetaceol.

00:08:51.840 --> 00:08:59.160
And we know about this entity of, you know, T cell lymphomas deriving from CAR-T,

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:02.400
especially there's been some publication with cetaceol.

00:09:02.720 --> 00:09:05.240
And this patient actually developed PTCL/NOS.

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:08.440
And when they were diagnosed, they had multiple TEP2 mutations.

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:13.600
We treated the patient with BVCHP, patient was quite frail.

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:15.640
It was too toxic and it didn't work.

00:09:16.880 --> 00:09:17.280
And

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:18.080
it's

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:18.440
sort of

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:18.440
a

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:18.440
lot,

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:18.560
it's sort of a lot,

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:19.520
it's sort of a lot, last-ditch effort.

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:21.200
We put the patient on Tazmetastat,

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:23.240
just single agent EZH2.

00:09:23.240 --> 00:09:27.280
And that resulted in a really, really remarkable response at three months.

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:30.240
Although it was not, it was short lived.

00:09:31.720 --> 00:09:33.680
And then lastly, I think Dr.

00:09:33.680 --> 00:09:37.880
Amiguel went over this study with ETCTN where

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:41.520
they were combining HTAC inhibitor with EZH2 inhibitor.

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:43.560
It has shown good outcomes.

00:09:43.560 --> 00:09:45.840
However, this study is closed now due to

00:09:46.880 --> 00:09:48.400
safety related

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:51.160
concerns with Tazmetastat.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:57.400
So with that, you know, this is my current management of systemic PTCLs.

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:00.200
I still consider CHOP or CHOAP

00:10:00.960 --> 00:10:05.280
in absence of clinical trials for TFH phenotype or PTCL/NOS.

00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:10.160
And for ALCL, I either consider BVCHP or BVCHEP,

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:14.720
followed by auto only for the ALK-negative ALCL patients.

00:10:15.160 --> 00:10:17.920
There is a major cooperative group trial

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:21.720
that's trying to combine either Duolacib or azacitidine

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:27.880
that's undergoing and that is, it is stratifying patient based on TFH versus non-TFH.

00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:29.560
So I think that will be important

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:33.560
once that trial gets going a little bit further.

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:36.200
And then for relapsed refractory,

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:40.600
I think I sort of put them in a bucket of eligible versus ineligible.

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:44.320
I try to use doublets or chemo for transplant eligible patients.

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:47.920
And for transplant ineligible patients, I try to use single agents.

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:49.320
Thank you.
